[As per the WHO Situation Report 98 from 27 Apr 2020 (https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/situation-reports/20200427-sitrep-98-covid-19.pdf and in COVID-19 update (136): UK NHS increased testing, Brazil, WHO 20200428.7274496), Spain has been reporting only PCR positive confirmations and not antibody based, effective 25 Apr 2020. The antibody confirmed cases are shown in the graph accompanying Table 1, but tabular form showing data by province is not available on the daily update website. That being said, Spain is 2nd globally in terms of the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19. There were 867 newly confirmed cases by PCR in the 24 hour period from 3 to 4 May 2020, bringing the PCR confirmed cumulative total to 219 329 [250 561] as compared with 218 011 PCR [248 301] confirmed cases on 3 May 2020 an increase from 356 change reported in yesterday's update (situation report 95 -- 4 May 2020), quite possibly due to post-weekend reporting artefact.

The countrywide 2-week incidence per 100 000 population continues to decrease and is now 47.24, a continual slow decrease over the past 26 days from a high of 214.43 on 7 Apr 2020 to 47.24 today (5 May 2020). Spain has the highest case count in Europe and is 2nd globally behind the USA in terms of absolute numbers of cases. Figure 1 at the source URL above shows the daily confirmations juxtaposed with dates of onset of disease, and one clearly sees the trend for decreasing confirmations in recent times. There is also a clear growth curve showing the trajectory of the epidemic at https://covid19.isciii.es/; it is updated daily.

Of the 219 329 [250 561] cases, approximately 119 609 (54.5%) [47.7%] -- an additional 720 cases have been hospitalized and 11 031 (5.0%) [4.4%] an additional 37 cases were admitted to the ICU (there is a note mentioning that some of the communities are providing daily prevalence data, hence my use of "approximately" for hospitalization and ICU data). 9.2% of hospitalized patients have been admitted to the ICU.

A map of Spain showing provinces (autonomous communities) can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/spain-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7304317,43. Catalonia, Castile and Leon, and La Rioja are still the most affected communities by population-based rates, even though their rates are dropping. Castile and Leon and neighboring La Rioja are located in the northern part of the country and Catalonia in the north east. - Mod.MPP]

