[7] Iran: resurgence
Date: Tue 5 May 2020
Source: Al Monitor [edited]
https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/05/iran-coronavirus-covid19-resurgence-pandemic-tehran-isfahan.html


A report released by Iran's Health Ministry says 15 out of the country's 31 provinces are experiencing a resurgence of the novel coronavirus pandemic, despite a flattened curve after more than 2 months of containment efforts. While the capital Tehran appeared to have begun a downward trend in cases, several popular tourism areas including Isfahan, Gilan and the pilgrimage city of Qom -- the epicenter of the outbreak -- are now facing another wave of infection.

The impoverished southern province of Hormozgan is also on the list. The growth in infections despite 36 degree Celsius temperatures (97 F) in Hormozgan once again dashed hopes that hot weather may subdue the virus. One Health Ministry test conducted in a Hormozgan seafood market alone identified over 100 cases of people who exhibited no obvious symptoms.

The resurgence has also slammed the oil-rich province of Khuzestan in the past 10 days, with governor Gholam-Reza Shariati blaming the situation on the "public's disregard" for social distancing measures. If the current trend holds, Shariati warned, the earlier restrictions will have to return in force.

Starting [11 Apr 2020], Iran introduced a phased relaxation of the strict containment measures, lifting travel bans and restoring much of the economy to pre-pandemic activity. The government also allowed religious gatherings to resume in mosques across 132 cities and Friday prayers in many more after mounting pressure from the conservative clergy, who argue that a continued closure on religious sites will deal an irreparable spiritual blow to the Iranian theocracy.

Nonetheless, deputy health minister Iraj Harirchi warned that even in those areas, designated as "COVID-19 white spots," the resumption of collective religious activities by no means indicates "the situation is back to normal", and that social distancing will have to drag on until the world finds a vaccine.

Questions surrounding how much longer those precautions will have to be observed remain an open debate in Iran, with some officials accused of serving as inappropriate examples by ignoring the measures before the public eye. Video from a [5 May 2020] parliament meeting broadcast on state TV showed speaker Ali Larijani -- a coronavirus survivor himself -- urging lawmakers to maintain the recommended distance from each other.

For several days in a row, Iran had registered double-digit mortality figures. But as of [5 May 2020], the total number of infected neared 100 000. Iran's flattened curve remains fragile, some experts have noted with serious concern about the return to normal. Iranian health officials sounded the alarm last month [April 2020] that it is only a matter of time before 2nd and 3rd waves of infection, a situation that would reimpose massive burdens on Iran's already overstretched 1st responders and sanctions-hit medical infrastructure.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The online link to the report is in Farsi and machine translation was used:
"According to reports, there is a possibility of a peak of corona prevalence in 15 provinces, which is on the rise, and in contrast, 9 provinces have had a declining trend against coronavirus.

"According to the Borno News Agency, and according to a report published by the Ministry of Health, the analysis of the trend of changes in the incidence of deaths and deaths reported on a daily basis has been used to evaluate the prevalence of COVID-19 disease in different provinces of the country. To calculate the trend of changes in death and morbidity in the last 5 days, first, the average 3-day number of reports of infection and death each day is calculated by averaging the data of the same day, the day before and the day after. Then, the increase rate was calculated each day compared to the previous day. Finally, the change in the incidence and death rate was calculated by averaging the numbers obtained for the last days. For better analysis, the indicators of the last 5 days were analyzed.

"The report of the Ministry of Health acknowledges that the following items have been considered for a possible analysis of the epidemic curve:

"According to the epidemiology committee of the Ministry of Health published in the information base of the Ministry of Health, the upward trend or peak of courier in 15 provinces (Qom, Lorestan, Ilam, Gilan, Golestan, Khorasan Razavi, Kohgiluyeh, and Boyer-Ahmad, Khuzestan, Hormozgan, Kerman, Yazd, Isfahan, Zanjan, Chaharmahal, Bakhtiari, and Kermanshah) are observed. Kurdistan Province is thought to have reached a stage of stability.

"9 provinces in the downward trend of coronavirus: Azerbaijan, Tehran, Alborz, Mazandaran, North Khorasan, Fars, Hamedan, Sistan, and Balochistan) show a downward trend.

"Probably 4 provinces (Qazvin, South Khorasan, West Azerbaijan, and Bushehr) have recently experienced an epidemic peak.

"The Ministry of Health also announced that data incompatibilities in the 2 provinces of Ardabil and Semnan would not allow an accurate analysis of the epidemic situation. Of course, one province can experience several curved peaks." (original available at https://tinyurl.com/yddr4uqf)

